  <p>
“This isn’t the sound of waves lapping against buildings—it’s the relentless hum of swarms. I’m on the eighth floor of Jinmao Tower, and outside, the city is alive with the incessant buzzing of mosquitoes carrying the deadly virus.”

“Boston…overrun by WNV?”

“Yes. It’s the last coastal stronghold, built high with defenses against nature—but the virus crept in from behind, unnoticed. Can you imagine the scene? Not the picturesque decay of an ancient city, but a nightmare: streets choked with abandoned vehicles, hospitals overrun by the infected, and a population too proud to use repellents or clear stagnant water. The once-vibrant metropolis now teems with death and decay.”

“Has the outbreak worsened?”

“Worse than anyone could have foreseen. In just a few decades, the virus mutated into a hyper-virulent strain. Coastal dwellers—three hundred million of them—fled inland, leaving behind desolation. The urban infrastructure crumbles, and the elderly and immunocompromised bear the brunt, succumbing to severe neurological damage and overwhelming epidemics. Our mission is to prevent this calamity.”

“You expect us to be gods?”

“Mortals who do the critical things a hundred years earlier can do God's work. If critical preventive measures had been taken a hundred years earlier, we might have been able to stop the outbreak. Imagine if, within a decade, every city had phased out pesticides and invested in strong mosquito control - if dependence on fossil fuels had been replaced with sustainable practices focused on public health. This disaster could have been avoided.

“It sounds impossible.”

“Perhaps. But our simulations show that if, from your time onward, every region abandoned old, ineffective practices in favor of strict mosquito surveillance and rapid vaccine deployment, the chain reaction could be broken. Every second counts. You have the knowledge now—a report, a paper—but every attempt you make is subtly sabotaged, censored by forces determined to keep this plague alive.”

